# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cpu-microarchitecture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In the history of computer hardware, some early reduced instruction set computer central processing units (RISC CPUs) used a very similar architectural solution, now called a **classic RISC pipeline**.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Those CPUs were: MIPS, SPARC, Motorola 88000, and later the notional CPU DLX invented for education.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Each of these classic scalar RISC designs fetches and tries to execute one instruction per cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The main common concept of each design is a five-stage execution instruction pipeline.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] During operation, each pipeline stage works on one instruction at a time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Each of these stages consists of a set of flip-flops to hold state, and combinational logic that operates on the outputs of those flip-flops.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The instructions reside in memory that takes one cycle to read.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] This memory can be dedicated to SRAM, or an Instruction Cache.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The term "latency" is used in computer science often and means the time from when an operation starts until it completes.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Thus, instruction fetch has a latency of one clock cycle (if using single-cycle SRAM or if the instruction was in the cache).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Thus, during the Instruction Fetch stage, a 32-bit instruction is fetched from the instruction memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The program counter (PC) is a register that holds the address that is presented to the instruction memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The address is presented to instruction memory at the start of a cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Then during the cycle, the instruction is read out of instruction memory, and at the same time, a calculation is done to determine the next PC.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The next PC is calculated by incrementing the PC by 4, and by choosing whether to take that as the next PC or to take the result of a branch/jump calculation as the next PC.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Note that in classic RISC, all instructions have the same length.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] (This is one thing that separates RISC from CISC).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In the original RISC designs, the size of an instruction is 4 bytes, so always add 4 to the instruction address, but don't use PC + 4 for the case of a taken branch, jump, or exception (see **delayed branches**, below).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Another thing that separates the first RISC machines from earlier CISC machines is that RISC has no microcode.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In the case of CISC micro-coded instructions, once fetched from the instruction cache, the instruction bits are shifted down the pipeline, where simple combinational logic in each pipeline stage produces control signals for the datapath directly from the instruction bits.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In those CISC designs, very little decoding is done in the stage traditionally called the decode stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] A consequence of this lack of decoding is that more instruction bits have to be used to specifying what the instruction does.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] That leaves fewer bits for things like register indices.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] All MIPS, SPARC, and DLX instructions have at most two register inputs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] During the decode stage, the indexes of these two registers are identified within the instruction, and the indexes are presented to the register memory, as the address.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Thus the two registers named are read from the register file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In the MIPS design, the register file had 32 entries.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] At the same time the register file is read, instruction issue logic in this stage determines if the pipeline is ready to execute the instruction in this stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] If not, the issue logic causes both the Instruction Fetch stage and the Decode stage to stall.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] On a stall cycle, the input flip flops do not accept new bits, thus no new calculations take place during that cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] If the instruction decoded is a branch or jump, the target address of the branch or jump is computed in parallel with reading the register file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The branch condition is computed in the following cycle (after the register file is read), and if the branch is taken or if the instruction is a jump, the PC in the first stage is assigned the branch target, rather than the incremented PC that has been computed.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Some architectures made use of the Arithmetic logic unit (ALU) in the Execute stage, at the cost of slightly decreased instruction throughput.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The decode stage ended up with quite a lot of hardware: MIPS has the possibility of branching if two registers are equal, so a 32-bit-wide AND tree runs in series after the register file read, making a very long critical path through this stage (which means fewer cycles per second).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Also, the branch target computation generally required a 16 bit add and a 14 bit incrementer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Resolving the branch in the decode stage made it possible to have just a single-cycle branch mis-predict penalty.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Since branches were very often taken (and thus mis-predicted), it was very important to keep this penalty low.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The Execute stage is where the actual computation occurs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Typically this stage consists of an ALU, and also a bit shifter.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] It may also include a multiple cycle multiplier and divider.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The ALU is responsible for performing Boolean operations (and, or, not, nand, nor, xor, xnor) and also for performing integer addition and subtraction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Besides the result, the ALU typically provides status bits such as whether or not the result was 0, or if an overflow occurred.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The bit shifter is responsible for shift and rotations.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] If data memory needs to be accessed, it is done in this stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] During this stage, single cycle latency instructions simply have their results forwarded to the next stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] This forwarding ensures that both one and two cycle instructions always write their results in the same stage of the pipeline so that just one write port to the register file can be used, and it is always available.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] For direct mapped and virtually tagged data caching, the simplest by far of the numerous data cache organizations, two SRAMs are used, one storing data and the other storing tags.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] During this stage, both single cycle and two cycle instructions write their results into the register file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Note that two different stages are accessing the register file at the same time—the decode stage is reading two source registers, at the same time that the writeback stage is writing a previous instruction's destination register.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] On real silicon, this can be a hazard (see below for more on hazards).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] That is because one of the source registers being read in decode might be the same as the destination register being written in writeback.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] When that happens, then the same memory cells in the register file are being both read and written the same time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] On silicon, many implementations of memory cells will not operate correctly when read and written at the same time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Hennessy and Patterson coined the term *hazard* for situations where instructions in a pipeline would produce wrong answers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Bypassing is also known as operand forwarding.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The instruction fetch and decode stages send the second instruction one cycle after the first.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In cycle 3, the `SUB` instruction calculates the new value for `r10`.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In the same cycle, the `AND` operation is decoded, and the value of `r10` is fetched from the register file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] However, the `SUB` instruction has not yet written its result to `r10`.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Write-back of this normally occurs in cycle 5 (green box).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Therefore, the value read from the register file and passed to the ALU (in the Execute stage of the `AND` operation, red box) is incorrect.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Instead, we must pass the data that was computed by `SUB` back to the Execute stage (i.e. to the red circle in the diagram) of the `AND` operation *before* it is normally written-back.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The solution to this problem is a pair of bypass multiplexers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] These multiplexers sit at the end of the decode stage, and their flopped outputs are the inputs to the ALU.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The current register pipeline of the access stage (which is either a loaded value or a forwarded ALU result, this provides bypassing of two stages): purple arrow.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Note that this requires the data to be passed *backwards* in time by one cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] If this occurs, a bubble must be inserted to stall the `AND` operation until the data is ready.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Decode stage logic compares the registers written by instructions in the execute and access stages of the pipeline to the registers read by the instruction in the decode stage, and cause the multiplexers to select the most recent data.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] These bypass multiplexers make it possible for the pipeline to execute simple instructions with just the latency of the ALU, the multiplexer, and a flip-flop.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Without the multiplexers, the latency of writing and then reading the register file would have to be included in the latency of these instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Note that the data can only be passed *forward* in time - the data cannot be bypassed back to an earlier stage if it has not been processed yet.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In the case above, the data is passed forward (by the time the `AND` is ready for the register in the ALU, the `SUB` has already computed it).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The data read from the address `adr` is not present in the data cache until after the Memory Access stage of the `LD` instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] By this time, the `AND` instruction is already through the ALU.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] To resolve this would require the data from memory to be passed backwards in time to the input to the ALU.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The solution is to delay the `AND` instruction by one cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The data hazard is detected in the decode stage, and the fetch and decode stages are **stalled** - they are prevented from flopping their inputs and so stay in the same state for a cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The execute, access, and write-back stages downstream see an extra no-operation instruction (NOP) inserted between the `LD` and `AND` instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] This NOP is termed a pipeline *bubble* since it floats in the pipeline, like an air bubble in a water pipe, occupying resources but not producing useful results.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The hardware to detect a data hazard and stall the pipeline until the hazard is cleared is called a **pipeline interlock**.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] A pipeline interlock does not have to be used with any data forwarding, however.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] This causes quite a performance hit, as the processor spends a lot of time processing nothing, but clock speeds can be increased as there is less forwarding logic to wait for.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] This data hazard can be detected quite easily when the program's machine code is written by the compiler.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The Stanford MIPS machine relied on the compiler to add the NOP instructions in this case, rather than having the circuitry to detect and (more taxingly) stall the first two pipeline stages.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Hence the name MIPS: Microprocessor without Interlocked Pipeline Stages.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] It turned out that the extra NOP instructions added by the compiler expanded the program binaries enough that the instruction cache hit rate was reduced.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The stall hardware, although expensive, was put back into later designs to improve instruction cache hit rate, at which point the acronym no longer made sense.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Delayed branches were controversial, first, because their semantics are complicated.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] A delayed branch specifies that the jump to a new location happens *after* the next instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] That next instruction is the one unavoidably loaded by the instruction cache after the branch.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Suppose a 32-bit RISC processes an ADD instruction that adds two large numbers, and the result does not fit in 32 bits.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The simplest solution, provided by most architectures, is wrapping arithmetic.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Numbers greater than the maximum possible encoded value have their most significant bits chopped off until they fit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The largest benefit of wrapping arithmetic is that every operation has a well defined result.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] But the programmer, especially if programming in a language supporting large integers (e.g.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Lisp or Scheme), may not want wrapping arithmetic.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] MIPS), define special addition operations that branch to special locations on overflow, rather than wrapping the result.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Software at the target location is responsible for fixing the problem.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] This special branch is called an exception.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Exceptions differ from regular branches in that the target address is not specified by the instruction itself, and the branch decision is dependent on the outcome of the instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The most common kind of software-visible exception on one of the classic RISC machines is a *TLB miss*.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Exceptions are different from branches and jumps, because those other control flow changes are resolved in the decode stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Exceptions are resolved in the writeback stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] When an exception is detected, the following instructions (earlier in the pipeline) are marked as invalid, and as they flow to the end of the pipe their results are discarded.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The program counter is set to the address of a special exception handler, and special registers are written with the exception location and cause.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] To make it easy (and fast) for the software to fix the problem and restart the program, the CPU must take a precise exception.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] A precise exception means that all instructions up to the excepting instruction have been executed, and the excepting instruction and everything afterwards have not been executed.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] To take precise exceptions, the CPU must *commit* changes to the software visible state in the program order.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] This in-order commit happens very naturally in the classic RISC pipeline.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Most instructions write their results to the register file in the writeback stage, and so those writes automatically happen in program order.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Store instructions, however, write their results to the Store Data Queue in the access stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] If the store instruction takes an exception, the Store Data Queue entry is invalidated so that it is not written to the cache data SRAM later.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Occasionally, either the data or instruction cache does not contain a required datum or instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] In these cases, the CPU must suspend operation until the cache can be filled with the necessary data, and then must resume execution.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The problem of filling the cache with the required data (and potentially writing back to memory the evicted cache line) is not specific to the pipeline organization, and is not discussed here.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] There are two strategies to handle the suspend/resume problem.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] This signal, when activated, prevents instructions from advancing down the pipeline, generally by gating off the clock to the flip-flops at the start of each stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The disadvantage of this strategy is that there are a large number of flip flops, so the global stall signal takes a long time to propagate.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Since the machine generally has to stall in the same cycle that it identifies the condition requiring the stall, the stall signal becomes a speed-limiting critical path.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] Another strategy to handle suspend/resume is to reuse the exception logic.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] The machine takes an exception on the offending instruction, and all further instructions are invalidated.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] When the cache has been filled with the necessary data, the instruction that caused the cache miss restarts.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/classic-risc-pipeline] To expedite data cache miss handling, the instruction can be restarted so that its access cycle happens one cycle after the data cache is filled.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] In the domain of central processing unit (CPU) design, **hazards** are problems with the instruction pipeline in CPU microarchitectures when the next instruction cannot execute in the following clock cycle, and can potentially lead to incorrect computation results.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Three common types of hazards are data hazards, structural hazards, and control hazards (branching hazards).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] There are several methods used to deal with hazards, including pipeline stalls/pipeline bubbling, operand forwarding, and in the case of out-of-order execution, the scoreboarding method and the Tomasulo algorithm.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Instructions in a pipelined processor are performed in several stages, so that at any given time several instructions are being processed in the various stages of the pipeline, such as fetch and execute.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] There are many different instruction pipeline microarchitectures, and instructions may be executed out-of-order.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] A hazard occurs when two or more of these simultaneous (possibly out of order) instructions conflict.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] A structural hazard occurs when two (or more) instructions which are already in a pipeline need the same resource.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] The result is that instructions must be executed in series rather than in parallel for a portion of the pipeline.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Structural hazards are sometimes referred to as resource hazards.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Example: A situation in which multiple instructions are ready to enter the execution phase but there is a single ALU (Arithmetic Logic Unit).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] One solution to this resource hazard is to increase available resources, by having multiple ports into main memory and multiple ALUs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Control hazard occurs when the control logic incorrectly predicts which program branch will be taken and therefore brings a sequence of instructions into the pipeline that are subsequently discarded.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] The term branch hazard also refers to a control hazard.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] The task of removing data dependencies can be delegated to the compiler, which can fill in an appropriate number of NOP instructions between dependent instructions to ensure correct operation, or re-order instructions where possible.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Following execution, register 2 should contain the value **10**.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] However, if i1 (write **3** to register 1) does not fully exit the pipeline before i2 starts executing, it means that R1 does not contain the value **3** when i2 performs its addition.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] This error occurs because i2 reads Register 1 before i1 has committed/stored the result of its write operation to Register 1.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] So when i2 is reading the contents of Register 1, register 1 still contains **6**, *not* **3**.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Forwarding (described below) helps correct such errors by depending on the fact that the output of i1 (which is **3**) can be used by subsequent instructions *before* the value **3** is committed to/stored in Register 1.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Added control logic is used to determine which input to use.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Memory latency is another factor that designers must attend to, because the delay could reduce performance.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Different types of memory have different accessing time to the memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/hazard-computer-architecture] Thus, by choosing a suitable type of memory, designers can improve the performance of the pipelined data path.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The **instruction cycle** (also known as the **fetch–decode–execute cycle**, or simply the **fetch–execute cycle**) is the cycle that the central processing unit (CPU) follows from boot-up until the computer has shut down in order to process instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] It is composed of three main stages: the fetch stage, the decode stage, and the execute stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] In simpler CPUs, the instruction cycle is executed sequentially, each instruction being processed before the next one is started.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] In most modern CPUs, the instruction cycles are instead executed concurrently, and often in parallel, through an instruction pipeline: the next instruction starts being processed before the previous instruction has finished, which is possible because the cycle is broken up into separate steps.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The program counter (PC) is a register that holds the memory address of the next instruction to be executed.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] After each instruction copy to the memory address register (MAR), the PC can either increment the pointer to the next sequential instruction, jump to a specified pointer, or branch conditionally to a specified pointer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] Also, during a CPU halt, the PC holds the instruction being executed, until an external interrupt or a reset signal is received.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The MAR is responsible for storing the address describing the location of the instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] After a read signal is initiated, the instruction in the address from the MAR is read and placed into the memory data register (MDR), also known as Memory Buffer Register (MBR).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] This component overall functions as an address buffer for pointing to locations in memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The MDR is responsible for temporarily holding instructions read from the address in MAR.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] It acts as a two-way register in the instruction cycle because it can take output from memory to the CPU, or output from the CPU to memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The current instruction register (CIR, though sometimes referred to as the instruction register, IR) is where the instruction is temporarily held, for the CPU to decode it and produce correct control signals for the execution stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The control unit (CU) decodes the instruction in the current instruction register (CIR).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] Then, the CU sends signals to other components within the CPU, such as the arithmetic logic unit (ALU), or back to memory to fetch operands, or to the floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The ALU performs arithmetic operations based on specific opcodes in the instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] For example, in RISC-V architecture, funct3 and funct7 opcodes exist to distinguish whether an instruction is a logical or arithmetic operation.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] **Decode stage**: During this stage, the encoded instruction in the CIR is interpreted by the CU.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] It determines what operations and additional operands are required for execution and sends respective signals to respective components within the CPU, such as the ALU or FPU, to prepare for the execution of the instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] **Execute stage**: This is the stage where the actual operation specified by the instruction is carried out by the relevant functional units of the CPU.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] Logical or arithmetic operations may be run by the ALU, data may be read from or written to memory, and the results are stored in registers or memory as required by the instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] Based on output from the ALU, the PC might branch.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] In addition, on most processors, interrupts can occur.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] This will cause the CPU to jump to an interrupt service routine, execute that, and then return to the instruction it was meant to be executing.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] In some cases, the instruction can be interrupted in the middle, but there will be no effect, and the instruction will be re-executed after return from the interrupt.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] This address is copied to the MAR, where this address is used to poll for the location of the instruction in memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The CU sends a signal to the control bus to read the memory at the address in MAR - the data read is placed in the data bus.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The data is transferred to the CPU via the data bus, where it's loaded into the MDR - at this stage, the PC increments by one.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The contents (instruction to-be-executed) of the MDR are copied into the CIR (where the instruction opcode and data operand can be decoded).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The decoding process allows the processor to determine what instruction is to be performed so that the CPU can tell how many operands it needs to fetch in order to perform the instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The opcode fetched from the memory is decoded for the next steps and moved to the appropriate registers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The decoding is typically performed by binary decoders in the CPU's CU.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] There are various ways that an architecture can specify determining the address for operands, usually called the addressing modes.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] The CPU sends the decoded instruction (decoded from the CU) as a set of control signals to corresponding components.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] This is the only stage of the instruction cycle that is useful from the perspective of the end-user.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-cycle] Everything else is overhead required to make the execute step happen.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In computer engineering, **instruction pipelining** is a technique for implementing instruction-level parallelism within a single processor.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining attempts to keep every part of the processor busy with some instruction by dividing incoming instructions into a series of sequential steps (the eponymous "pipeline") performed by different processor units with different parts of instructions processed in parallel.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In a pipelined computer, instructions travel through the central processing unit (CPU) in stages.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] For example, it might have one stage for each step of the von Neumann cycle: Fetch the instruction, fetch the operands, do the instruction, write the results.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined computer usually has "pipeline registers" after each stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] These store information from the instruction and calculations so that the logic gates of the next stage can do the next step.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] This arrangement lets the CPU complete an instruction on each clock cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] It is common for even-numbered stages to operate on one edge of the square-wave clock, while odd-numbered stages operate on the other edge.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] This allows more CPU throughput than a multicycle computer at a given clock rate, but may increase latency due to the added overhead of the pipelining process itself.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Also, even though the electronic logic has a fixed maximum speed, a pipelined computer can be made faster or slower by varying the number of stages in the pipeline.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] With more stages, each stage does less work, and so the stage has fewer delays from the logic gates and could run at a higher clock rate.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined model of computer is often the most economical, when cost is measured as logic gates per instruction per second.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] At each instant, an instruction is in only one pipeline stage, and on average, a pipeline stage is less costly than a multicycle computer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Also, when made well, most of the pipelined computer's logic is in use most of the time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In contrast, out of order computers usually have large amounts of idle logic at any given instant.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Similar calculations usually show that a pipelined computer uses less energy per instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] However, a pipelined computer is usually more complex and more costly than a comparable multicycle computer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] It typically has more logic gates, registers and a more complex control unit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In a like way, it might use more total energy, while using less energy per instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Out of order CPUs can usually do more instructions per second because they can do several instructions at once.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In a pipelined computer, the control unit arranges for the flow to start, continue, and stop as a program commands.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The instruction data is usually passed in pipeline registers from one stage to the next, with a somewhat separated piece of control logic for each stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The control unit also assures that the instruction in each stage does not harm the operation of instructions in other stages.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] For example, if two stages must use the same piece of data, the control logic assures that the uses are done in the correct sequence.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] When operating efficiently, a pipelined computer will have an instruction in each stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] It is then working on all of those instructions at the same time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] It can finish about one instruction for each cycle of its clock.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] But when a program switches to a different sequence of instructions, the pipeline sometimes must discard the data in process and restart.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Much of the design of a pipelined computer prevents interference between the stages and reduces stalls.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The number of dependent steps varies with the machine architecture.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] As the pipeline is made "deeper" (with a greater number of dependent steps), a given step can be implemented with simpler circuitry, which may let the processor clock run faster.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A processor is said to be *fully pipelined* if it can fetch an instruction on every cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Thus, if some instructions or conditions require delays that inhibit fetching new instructions, the processor is not fully pipelined.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Seminal uses of pipelining were in the ILLIAC II project and the IBM Stretch project, though a simple version was used earlier in the Z1 in 1939 and the Z3 in 1941.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining began in earnest in the late 1970s in supercomputers such as vector processors and array processors.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] One of the early supercomputers was the Cyber series built by Control Data Corporation.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Its main architect, Seymour Cray, later headed Cray Research.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Cray developed the XMP line of supercomputers, using pipelining for both multiply and add/subtract functions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Later, Star Technologies added parallelism (several pipelined functions working in parallel), developed by Roger Chen.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In 1984, Star Technologies added the pipelined divide circuit developed by James Bradley.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining was not limited to supercomputers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In 1976, the Amdahl Corporation's 470 series general purpose mainframe had a 7-step pipeline, and a patented branch prediction circuit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A central element in RISC design philosophy, by the mid-1980s, pipelining was also being introduced into traditional CISC architectures by their developers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The model of sequential execution assumes that each instruction completes before the next one begins; this assumption is not true on a pipelined processor.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A situation where the expected result is problematic is known as a hazard.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] If the processor has the 5 steps listed in the initial illustration (the 'Basic five-stage pipeline' at the start of the article), instruction 1 would be fetched at time *t*1 and its execution would be complete at *t5*.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Instruction 2 would be fetched at *t2* and would be complete at *t6*.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The first instruction might deposit the incremented number into R5 as its fifth step (register write back) at *t5*.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] But the second instruction might get the number from R5 (to copy to R6) in its second step (instruction decode and register fetch) at time *t3*.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] It seems that the first instruction would not have incremented the value by then.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Writing computer programs in a compiled language might not raise these concerns, as the compiler could be designed to generate machine code that avoids hazards.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The programmer may have unrelated work that the processor can do in the meantime; or, to ensure correct results, the programmer may insert NOPs into the code, partly negating the advantages of pipelining.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A branch out of the normal instruction sequence often involves a hazard.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Unless the processor can give effect to the branch in a single time cycle, the pipeline will continue fetching instructions sequentially.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Such instructions cannot be allowed to take effect because the programmer has diverted control to another part of the program.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A conditional branch is even more problematic.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The processor may or may not branch, depending on a calculation that has not yet occurred.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Various processors may stall, may attempt branch prediction, and may be able to begin to execute two different program sequences (eager execution), each assuming the branch is or is not taken, discarding all work that pertains to the incorrect guess.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A processor with an implementation of branch prediction that usually makes correct predictions can minimize the performance penalty from branching.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] However, if branches are predicted poorly, it may create more work for the processor, such as flushing from the pipeline the incorrect code path that has begun execution before resuming execution at the correct location.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Programs written for a pipelined processor deliberately avoid branching to minimize possible loss of speed.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] For example, the programmer can handle the usual case with sequential execution and branch only on detecting unusual cases.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Using programs such as gcov to analyze code coverage lets the programmer measure how often particular branches are actually executed and gain insight with which to optimize the code.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In some cases, a programmer can handle both the usual case and unusual case with branch-free code.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] can be problematic on a pipelined processor.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In this technique, one of the effects of a program is to modify its own upcoming instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] and the modification will not take effect.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] can configure their on-chip cache memories for data-only fetches, or as part of their ordinary memory address space, and avoid such difficulties with self-modifying instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] between instructions, but a pipelining processor overlaps instructions, so executing an uninterruptible instruction renders portions of ordinary instructions uninterruptible too.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] a single-core system using an infinite loop in which an uninterruptible instruction was always in the pipeline.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining keeps all portions of the processor occupied and increases the amount of useful work the processor can do in a given time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining typically reduces the processor's cycle time and increases the throughput of instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] that require execution to slow below its ideal rate.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A non-pipelined processor executes only a single instruction at a time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The start of the next instruction is delayed not based on hazards but unconditionally.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined processor's need to organize all its work into modular steps may require the duplication of registers, which increases the latency of some instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] By making each dependent step simpler, pipelining can enable complex operations more economically than adding complex circuitry, such as for numerical calculations.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] However, a processor that declines to pursue increased speed with pipelining may be simpler and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Compared to environments where the programmer needs to avoid or work around hazards, use of a non-pipelined processor may make it easier to program and to train programmers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The non-pipelined processor also makes it easier to predict the exact timing of a given sequence of instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] To the right is a generic pipeline with four stages: fetch, decode, execute and write-back.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The top gray box is the list of instructions waiting to be executed, the bottom gray box is the list of instructions that have had their execution completed, and the middle white box is the pipeline.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined processor may deal with hazards by stalling and creating a bubble in the pipeline, resulting in one or more cycles in which nothing useful happens.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] In the illustration at right, in cycle 3, the processor cannot decode the purple instruction, perhaps because the processor determines that decoding depends on results produced by the execution of the green instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The green instruction can proceed to the Execute stage and then to the Write-back stage as scheduled, but the purple instruction is stalled for one cycle at the Fetch stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] The blue instruction, which was due to be fetched during cycle 3, is stalled for one cycle, as is the red instruction after it.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Because of the bubble (the blue ovals in the illustration), the processor's Decode circuitry is idle during cycle 3.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] Its Execute circuitry is idle during cycle 4 and its Write-back circuitry is idle during cycle 5.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] When the bubble moves out of the pipeline (at cycle 6), normal execution resumes.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/instruction-pipelining] It will take 8 cycles (cycle 1 through 8) rather than 7 to completely execute the four instructions shown in colors.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In electronics, computer science and computer engineering, **microarchitecture**, also called **computer organization** and sometimes abbreviated as **μarch** or **uarch**, is the way a given instruction set architecture (ISA) is implemented in a particular processor.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] A given ISA may be implemented with different microarchitectures; implementations may vary due to different goals of a given design or due to shifts in technology.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Computer architecture is the combination of microarchitecture and instruction set architecture.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The ISA is roughly the same as the programming model of a processor as seen by an assembly language programmer or compiler writer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The ISA includes the instructions, execution model, processor registers, address and data formats among other things.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The microarchitecture includes the constituent parts of the processor and how these interconnect and interoperate to implement the ISA.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] These diagrams generally separate the datapath (where data is placed) and the control path (which can be said to steer the data).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The person designing a system usually draws the specific microarchitecture as a kind of data flow diagram.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Like a block diagram, the microarchitecture diagram shows microarchitectural elements such as the arithmetic and logic unit and the register file as a single schematic symbol.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Very simple computers have a single data bus organization – they have a single three-state bus.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The diagram of more complex computers usually shows multiple three-state buses, which help the machine do more operations simultaneously.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Each microarchitectural element is in turn represented by a schematic describing the interconnections of logic gates used to implement it.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Each logic gate is in turn represented by a circuit diagram describing the connections of the transistors used to implement it in some particular logic family.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Machines with different microarchitectures may have the same instruction set architecture, and thus be capable of executing the same programs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] New microarchitectures and/or circuitry solutions, along with advances in semiconductor manufacturing, are what allows newer generations of processors to achieve higher performance while using the same ISA.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In principle, a single microarchitecture could execute several different ISAs with only minor changes to the microcode.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The pipelined datapath is the most commonly used datapath design in microarchitecture today.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This technique is used in most modern microprocessors, microcontrollers, and DSPs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The pipelined architecture allows multiple instructions to overlap in execution, much like an assembly line.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The pipeline includes several different stages which are fundamental in microarchitecture designs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Some of these stages include instruction fetch, instruction decode, execute, and write back.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Some architectures include other stages such as memory access.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The design of pipelines is one of the central microarchitectural tasks.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Execution units are also essential to microarchitecture.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Execution units include arithmetic logic units (ALU), floating point units (FPU), load/store units, branch prediction, and SIMD.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] These units perform the operations or calculations of the processor.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The choice of the number of execution units, their latency and throughput is a central microarchitectural design task.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The size, latency, throughput and connectivity of memories within the system are also microarchitectural decisions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] System-level design decisions such as whether or not to include peripherals, such as memory controllers, can be considered part of the microarchitectural design process.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This includes decisions on the performance-level and connectivity of these peripherals.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Unlike architectural design, where achieving a specific performance level is the main goal, microarchitectural design pays closer attention to other constraints.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Since microarchitecture design decisions directly affect what goes into a system, attention must be paid to issues such as chip area/cost, power consumption, logic complexity, ease of connectivity, manufacturability, ease of debugging, and testability.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The instruction cycle is repeated continuously until the power is turned off.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Historically, the earliest computers were multicycle designs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The smallest, least-expensive computers often still use this technique.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Multicycle architectures often use the least total number of logic elements and reasonable amounts of power.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] They can be designed to have deterministic timing and high reliability.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In particular, they have no pipeline to stall when taking conditional branches or interrupts.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] However, other microarchitectures often perform more instructions per unit time, using the same logic family.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] When discussing "improved performance," an improvement is often relative to a multicycle design.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In a multicycle computer, the computer does the four steps in sequence, over several cycles of the clock.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Some designs can perform the sequence in two clock cycles by completing successive stages on alternate clock edges, possibly with longer operations occurring outside the main cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] For example, stage one on the rising edge of the first cycle, stage two on the falling edge of the first cycle, etc.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In the control logic, the combination of cycle counter, cycle state (high or low) and the bits of the instruction decode register determine exactly what each part of the computer should be doing.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] To design the control logic, one can create a table of bits describing the control signals to each part of the computer in each cycle of each instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Then, this logic table can be tested in a software simulation running test code.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] If the logic table is placed in a memory and used to actually run a real computer, it is called a microprogram.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In some computer designs, the logic table is optimized into the form of combinational logic made from logic gates, usually using a computer program that optimizes logic.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Early computers used ad-hoc logic design for control until Maurice Wilkes invented this tabular approach and called it microprogramming.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Complicating this simple-looking series of steps is the fact that the memory hierarchy, which includes caching, main memory and non-volatile storage like hard disks (where the program instructions and data reside), has always been slower than the processor itself.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Step (2) often introduces a lengthy (in CPU terms) delay while the data arrives over the computer bus.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] A considerable amount of research has been put into designs that avoid these delays as much as possible.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Over the years, a central goal was to execute more instructions in parallel, thus increasing the effective execution speed of a program.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] These efforts introduced complicated logic and circuit structures.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Initially, these techniques could only be implemented on expensive mainframes or supercomputers due to the amount of circuitry needed for these techniques.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] As semiconductor manufacturing progressed, more and more of these techniques could be implemented on a single semiconductor chip.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Instruction sets have shifted over the years, from originally very simple to sometimes very complex (in various respects).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In recent years, load–store architectures, VLIW and EPIC types have been in fashion.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Architectures that are dealing with data parallelism include SIMD and Vectors.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Some labels used to denote classes of CPU architectures are not particularly descriptive, especially so the CISC label; many early designs retroactively denoted "CISC" are in fact significantly simpler than modern RISC processors (in several respects).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] However, the choice of instruction set architecture may greatly affect the complexity of implementing high-performance devices.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The prominent strategy, used to develop the first RISC processors, was to simplify instructions to a minimum of individual semantic complexity combined with high encoding regularity and simplicity.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] One of the first, and most powerful, techniques to improve performance is the use of instruction pipelining.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Early processor designs would carry out all of the steps above for one instruction before moving onto the next.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Large portions of the circuitry were left idle at any one step; for instance, the instruction decoding circuitry would be idle during execution and so on.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Pipelining improves performance by allowing a number of instructions to work their way through the processor at the same time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In the same basic example, the processor would start to decode (step 1) a new instruction while the last one was waiting for results.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This would allow up to four instructions to be "in flight" at one time, making the processor look four times as fast.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Although any one instruction takes just as long to complete (there are still four steps) the CPU as a whole "retires" instructions much faster.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] RISC makes pipelines smaller and much easier to construct by cleanly separating each stage of the instruction process and making them take the same amount of time—one cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The processor as a whole operates in an assembly line fashion, with instructions coming in one side and results out the other.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Due to the reduced complexity of the classic RISC pipeline, the pipelined core and an instruction cache could be placed on the same size die that would otherwise fit the core alone on a CISC design.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This was the real reason that RISC was faster.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Early designs like the SPARC and MIPS often ran over 10 times as fast as Intel and Motorola CISC solutions at the same clock speed and price.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Pipelines are by no means limited to RISC designs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] By 1986 the top-of-the-line VAX implementation (VAX 8800) was a heavily pipelined design, slightly predating the first commercial MIPS and SPARC designs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Most modern CPUs (even embedded CPUs) are now pipelined, and microcoded CPUs with no pipelining are seen only in the most area-constrained embedded processors.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Large CISC machines, from the VAX 8800 to the modern Intel and AMD processors, are implemented with both microcode and pipelines.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Improvements in pipelining and caching are the two major microarchitectural advances that have enabled processor performance to keep pace with the circuit technology on which they are based.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] It was not long before improvements in chip manufacturing allowed for even more circuitry to be placed on the die, and designers started looking for ways to use it.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] One of the most common was to add an ever-increasing amount of cache memory on-die.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Cache is very fast and expensive memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] It can be accessed in a few cycles as opposed to many needed to "talk" to main memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The CPU includes a cache controller which automates reading and writing from the cache.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] If the data is already in the cache it is accessed from there – at considerable time savings, whereas if it is not the processor is "stalled" while the cache controller reads it in.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] RISC designs started adding cache in the mid-to-late 1980s, often only 4 KB in total.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This number grew over time, and typical CPUs now have at least 2 MB, while more powerful CPUs come with 4 or 6 or 12MB or even 32MB or more, with the most being 768MB in the newly released EPYC Milan-X line, organized in multiple levels of a memory hierarchy.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Generally speaking, more cache means more performance, due to reduced stalling.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Caches and pipelines were a perfect match for each other.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Previously, it didn't make much sense to build a pipeline that could run faster than the access latency of off-chip memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Using on-chip cache memory instead, meant that a pipeline could run at the speed of the cache access latency, a much smaller length of time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This allowed the operating frequencies of processors to increase at a much faster rate than that of off-chip memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] One barrier to achieving higher performance through instruction-level parallelism stems from pipeline stalls and flushes due to branches.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Normally, whether a conditional branch will be taken isn't known until late in the pipeline as conditional branches depend on results coming from a register.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] As clock speeds increase the depth of the pipeline increases with it, and some modern processors may have 20 stages or more.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] On average, every fifth instruction executed is a branch, so without any intervention, that's a high amount of stalling.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Techniques such as branch prediction and speculative execution are used to lessen these branch penalties.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Branch prediction is where the hardware makes educated guesses on whether a particular branch will be taken.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In reality one side or the other of the branch will be called much more often than the other.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Modern designs have rather complex statistical prediction systems, which watch the results of past branches to predict the future with greater accuracy.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The guess allows the hardware to prefetch instructions without waiting for the register read.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Speculative execution is a further enhancement in which the code along the predicted path is not just prefetched but also executed before it is known whether the branch should be taken or not.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This can yield better performance when the guess is good, with the risk of a huge penalty when the guess is bad because instructions need to be undone.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Even with all of the added complexity and gates needed to support the concepts outlined above, improvements in semiconductor manufacturing soon allowed even more logic gates to be used.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In the outline above the processor processes parts of a single instruction at a time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Computer programs could be executed faster if multiple instructions were processed simultaneously.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This is what superscalar processors achieve, by replicating functional units such as ALUs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The replication of functional units was only made possible when the die area of a single-issue processor no longer stretched the limits of what could be reliably manufactured.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] By the late 1980s, superscalar designs started to enter the market place.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In modern designs it is common to find two load units, one store (many instructions have no results to store), two or more integer math units, two or more floating point units, and often a SIMD unit of some sort.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The instruction issue logic grows in complexity by reading in a huge list of instructions from memory and handing them off to the different execution units that are idle at that point.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The results are then collected and re-ordered at the end.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The addition of caches reduces the frequency or duration of stalls due to waiting for data to be fetched from the memory hierarchy, but does not get rid of these stalls entirely.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In early designs a *cache miss* would force the cache controller to stall the processor and wait.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Of course there may be some other instruction in the program whose data *is* available in the cache at that point.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Out-of-order execution allows that ready instruction to be processed while an older instruction waits on the cache, then re-orders the results to make it appear that everything happened in the programmed order.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This technique is also used to avoid other operand dependency stalls, such as an instruction awaiting a result from a long latency floating-point operation or other multi-cycle operations.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Register renaming refers to a technique used to avoid unnecessary serialized execution of program instructions because of the reuse of the same registers by those instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Suppose we have two groups of instruction that will use the same register.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] One set of instructions is executed first to leave the register to the other set, but if the other set is assigned to a different similar register, both sets of instructions can be executed in parallel (or) in series.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Computer architects have become stymied by the growing mismatch in CPU operating frequencies and DRAM access times.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] None of the techniques that exploited instruction-level parallelism (ILP) within one program could make up for the long stalls that occurred when data had to be fetched from main memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Additionally, the large transistor counts and high operating frequencies needed for the more advanced ILP techniques required power dissipation levels that could no longer be cheaply cooled.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] For these reasons, newer generations of computers have started to exploit higher levels of parallelism that exist outside of a single program or program thread.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This trend is sometimes known as *throughput computing*.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This idea originated in the mainframe market where online transaction processing emphasized not just the execution speed of one transaction, but the capacity to deal with massive numbers of transactions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] With transaction-based applications such as network routing and web-site serving greatly increasing in the last decade, the computer industry has re-emphasized capacity and throughput issues.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] One technique of how this parallelism is achieved is through multiprocessing systems, computer systems with multiple CPUs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Once reserved for high-end mainframes and supercomputers, small-scale (2–8) multiprocessors servers have become commonplace for the small business market.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] For large corporations, large scale (16–256) multiprocessors are common.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Even personal computers with multiple CPUs have appeared since the 1990s.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] With further transistor size reductions made available with semiconductor technology advances, multi-core CPUs have appeared where multiple CPUs are implemented on the same silicon chip.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Initially used in chips targeting embedded markets, where simpler and smaller CPUs would allow multiple instantiations to fit on one piece of silicon.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] By 2005, semiconductor technology allowed dual high-end desktop CPUs *CMP* chips to be manufactured in volume.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Some designs, such as Sun Microsystems' UltraSPARC T1 have reverted to simpler (scalar, in-order) designs in order to fit more processors on one piece of silicon.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Another technique that has become more popular recently is multithreading.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] In multithreading, when the processor has to fetch data from slow system memory, instead of stalling for the data to arrive, the processor switches to another program or program thread which is ready to execute.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Though this does not speed up a particular program/thread, it increases the overall system throughput by reducing the time the CPU is idle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] Conceptually, multithreading is equivalent to a context switch at the operating system level.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] The difference is that a multithreaded CPU can do a thread switch in one CPU cycle instead of the hundreds or thousands of CPU cycles a context switch normally requires.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This is achieved by replicating the state hardware (such as the register file and program counter) for each active thread.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] A further enhancement is simultaneous multithreading.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/microarchitecture] This technique allows superscalar CPUs to execute instructions from different programs/threads simultaneously in the same cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In computer architecture, **register renaming** is a technique that abstracts logical registers from physical registers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Every logical register has a set of physical registers associated with it.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] When a machine language instruction refers to a particular logical register, the processor transposes this name to one specific physical register on the fly.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The physical registers are opaque and cannot be referenced directly but only via the canonical names.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This technique is used to eliminate false data dependencies arising from the reuse of registers by successive instructions that do not have any real data dependencies between them.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The elimination of these false data dependencies reveals more instruction-level parallelism in an instruction stream, which can be exploited by various and complementary techniques such as superscalar and out-of-order execution for better performance.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Programs are composed of instructions which operate on values.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The instructions must name these values in order to distinguish them from one another.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] A typical instruction might say: add x and y and put the result in z .
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In this instruction, x , y and z are the names of storage locations.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] It is common for the values being manipulated to be used several times in succession.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Register machines take advantage of this by introducing a number of processor registers, which are high-speed memory locations that hold these values.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Since register access is typically much faster than accessing memory, high-performance code and processors try to operate on registers when possible.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The collection of registers in a particular design is known as its *register file*.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Individual registers in the file are referred to by number in the machine code.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Encoding a number in the machine code requires several bits.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] For instance, in the Zilog Z80 there were eight general-purpose registers in the file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] To select one of eight values requires three bits, as 23 = 8.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] More architectural (logical) registers of the same width and type can result in better performance, as more temporary values can be held in registers and thus avoid the expensive operations of saving or loading from memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Similarly, wider registers that can hold more data can also improve performance, if the workload can make use of that.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Generally, more modern processors and those with larger instruction words will use more registers when possible.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] For example, the IA-32 instruction set architecture has 8 general purpose registers, x86-64 has 16, many RISCs have 32, and IA-64 has 128.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The advantages of a larger register file are offset by the need to use more bits to encode the register number.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] For instance, in a system using 32-bit instructions, you might wish to have three registers, such that you can perform operations of the type z = $x+y$ .
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] If the register file contains 32 entries, each one of the references will require 5 bits, and the set of three registers thus takes up 15 bits, leaving 17 to encode the operation and other information.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Expanding the register file to 64 entries would require 6 bits, a total of 18 bits.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] While this may result in faster performance, it also means there are fewer bits left over for encoding the instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This leads to an effort to balance the size of the file with the number of possible instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Processors in early computers often worked lock-step with their main memory, which reduced the advantages of large register files.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This made the instructions smaller, and thus faster to read.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This sort of design, which maximized performance by carefully tuning the instruction set for minimal size, was common until the 1980s.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] An example of this approach is the MOS 6502, which had only a single register, in which case it is referred to as the accumulator, and a special "zero page" addressing mode for the first 256 bytes of memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Placing code and data in the zero page meant the instruction was only two bytes long instead of three, greatly improving performance through avoided reads, providing similar benefits to having more registers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The widespread introduction of dynamic RAM in the 1970s changed this approach.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Over time, the performance of the central processing units (CPUs) increased relative to the memory they were attached to, it was no longer reasonable to use main memory as registers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This led to increasingly large register files, internal to the CPU, to avoid referring to memory wherever possible.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] However, it is not possible to avoid accessing memory entirely in practice, and as the speed difference grew, every such access became more and more expensive in terms of the number of instructions that might be performed had the value been in a register.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Different instructions may take different amounts of time; for example, a processor may be able to execute hundreds of register-to-register instructions while a single load from the main memory is in progress.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] A key advance in improving performance is to allow those fast instructions to be performed while the others are waiting for data.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This means the instructions are no longer completed in the order they are specified in the machine code, they are instead performed out-of-order.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The instructions in the final three lines are independent of the first three instructions, but the processor cannot finish `r1 ≔ m[2048]` until the preceding `m[1032] ≔ r1` is complete, as doing so would add four to the value of 1024, not 2048.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Now the last three instructions can be executed in parallel with the first three.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The program will run faster than before by eliminating the data dependency caused by unnecessarily using the same register in both sequences.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] A compiler can detect independent instruction sequences and, if there are registers that are available for use, choose different registers during register allocation in the code generation process.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] with register r1 "renamed" to the internal register rA for the first three instructions and to the internal register rB for the second three instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This removes the false data dependency, allowing the first three instructions to be executed in parallel with the second three instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] a read from a register or memory location must return the value placed there by the last write in program order, not some other write.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] , and requires the instructions to execute in program order.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] successive writes to a particular register or memory location must leave that location containing the result of the second write.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] (also known as cancelling, annulling, or mooting) the first write if necessary.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] a read from a register or memory location must return the last prior value written to that location, and not one written programmatically after the read.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Instead of delaying the write until all reads are completed, two copies of the location can be maintained, the old value and the new value.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Reads that precede, in program order, the write of the new value can be provided with the old value, even while other reads that follow the write are provided with the new value.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The false dependency is broken and additional opportunities for out-of-order execution are created.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] When all reads that need the old value have been satisfied, it can be discarded.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This is the essential concept behind register renaming.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Anything that is read and written can be renamed.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] While the general-purpose and floating-point registers are discussed the most, flag and status registers or even individual status bits are commonly renamed as well.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Memory locations can also be renamed, although it is not commonly done to the extent practiced in register renaming.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The Transmeta Crusoe processor's gated store buffer is a form of memory renaming.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] If programs refrained from reusing registers immediately, there would be no need for register renaming.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Some instruction sets (e.g., IA-64) specify very large numbers of registers for specifically this reason.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Code size increases are important because when the program code is larger, the instruction cache misses more often and the processor stalls waiting for new instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Machine language programs specify reads and writes to a limited set of registers specified by the instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] For instance, the Alpha ISA specifies 32 integer registers, each 64 bits wide, and 32 floating-point registers, each 64 bits wide.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] These are the *architectural* registers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Programs written for processors running the Alpha instruction set will specify operations reading and writing those 64 registers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] If a programmer stops the program in a debugger, they can observe the contents of these 64 registers (and a few status registers) to determine the progress of the machine.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] One particular processor which implements this ISA, the Alpha 21264, has 80 integer and 72 floating-point *physical* registers.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The following text describes two styles of register renaming, which are distinguished by the circuit which holds the data ready for an execution unit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In all renaming schemes, the machine converts the architectural registers referenced in the instruction stream into tags.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Where the architectural registers might be specified by 3 to 5 bits, the tags are usually a 6 to 8 bit number.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The rename file must have a read port for every input of every instruction renamed every cycle, and a write port for every output of every instruction renamed every cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Because the size of a register file generally grows as the square of the number of ports, the rename file is usually physically large and consumes significant power.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In the *tag-indexed register file* style, there is one large register file for data values, containing one register for every tag.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] For example, if the machine has 80 physical registers, then it would use 7 bit tags.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] 48 of the possible tag values in this case are unused.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In this style, when an instruction is issued to an execution unit, the tags of the source registers are sent to the physical register file, where the values corresponding to those tags are read and sent to the execution unit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In the *reservation station* style, there are many small associative register files, usually one at the inputs to each execution unit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Each operand of each instruction in an issue queue has a place for a value in one of these register files.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In this style, when an instruction is issued to an execution unit, the register file entries corresponding to the issue queue entry are read and forwarded to the execution unit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The committed register state of the machine.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Typically written into as results are retired or committed out of a reorder buffer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The most speculative register state of the machine.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The Intel P6 group's term for Future File.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Typically used in combination with a future file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Contains the "old" values of registers that have been overwritten.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] If the producer is still in flight it may be RAM indexed by history buffer number.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] (CAM) indexed by logical register number.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] A structure that is sequentially (circularly) indexed on a per-operation basis, for instructions in flight.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] It differs from a history buffer because the reorder buffer typically comes after the future file (if it exists) and before the architectural register file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Reorder buffers can be data-less or data-ful.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Some examples: In Willamette's ROB, the ROB entries point to registers in the physical register file (PRF), and also contain other book keeping.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This was also the first Out of Order design done by Andy Glew, at Illinois with HaRRM.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] P6's ROB, the ROB entries contain data; there is no separate PRF.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Data values from the ROB are copied from the ROB to the RRF at retirement.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] One small detail: if there is temporal locality in ROB entries (i.e., if instructions close together in the von Neumann instruction sequence write back close together in time, it may be possible to perform write combining on ROB entries and so have fewer ports than a separate ROB/PRF would).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] It is not clear if it makes a difference, since a PRF should be banked.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] ROBs usually don't have associative logic, and certainly none of the ROBs designed by Andy Glew have CAMs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] insisted that ROBs have complex associative logic for many years.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The first ROB proposal may have had CAMs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This is the renaming style used in the MIPS R10000, the Alpha 21264, and in the FP section of the AMD Athlon.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In the renaming stage, every architectural register referenced (for read or write) is looked up in an architecturally-indexed **remap file**.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This file returns a tag and a ready bit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The tag is non-ready if there is a queued instruction which will write to it that has not yet executed.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] For read operands, this tag takes the place of the architectural register in the instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] For every register write, a new tag is pulled from a free tag FIFO, and a new mapping is written into the remap file, so that future instructions reading the architectural register will refer to this new tag.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The tag is marked as unready, because the instruction has not yet executed.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The previous physical register allocated for that architectural register is saved with the instruction in the reorder buffer, which is a FIFO that holds the instructions in program order between the decode and graduation stages.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The instructions are then placed in various **issue queues**.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] As instructions are executed, the tags for their results are broadcast, and the issue queues match these tags against the tags of their non-ready source operands.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] A match means that the operand is ready.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The remap file also matches these tags, so that it can mark the corresponding physical registers as ready.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] When all the operands of an instruction in an issue queue are ready, that instruction is ready to issue.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The issue queues pick ready instructions to send to the various functional units each cycle.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Non-ready instructions stay in the issue queues.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This unordered removal of instructions from the issue queues can make them large and power-consuming.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Issued instructions read from a tag-indexed physical register file (bypassing just-broadcast operands) and then execute.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Execution results are written to tag-indexed physical register file, as well as broadcast to the bypass network preceding each functional unit.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Graduation puts the previous tag for the written architectural register into the free queue so that it can be reused for a newly decoded instruction.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] An exception or branch misprediction causes the remap file to back up to the remap state at last valid instruction via combination of state snapshots and cycling through the previous tags in the in-order pre-graduation queue.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Since this mechanism is required, and since it can recover any remap state (not just the state before the instruction currently being graduated), branch mispredictions can be handled before the branch reaches graduation, potentially hiding the branch misprediction latency.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This is the style used in the integer section of the AMD K7 and K8 designs.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In the renaming stage, every architectural register referenced for reads is looked up in both the architecturally-indexed **future file** and the rename file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The future file read gives the value of that register, if there is no outstanding instruction yet to write to it (i.e., it's ready).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] When the instruction is placed in an issue queue, the values read from the future file are written into the corresponding entries in the reservation stations.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Register writes in the instruction cause a new, non-ready tag to be written into the rename file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The tag number is usually serially allocated in instruction order—no free tag FIFO is necessary.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Just as with the tag-indexed scheme, the issue queues wait for non-ready operands to see matching tag broadcasts.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Unlike the tag-indexed scheme, matching tags cause the corresponding broadcast value to be written into the issue queue entry's reservation station.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Issued instructions read their arguments from the reservation station, bypass just-broadcast operands, and then execute.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] As mentioned earlier, the reservation station register files are usually small, with perhaps eight entries.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Execution results are written to the reorder buffer, to the reservation stations (if the issue queue entry has a matching tag), and to the future file if this is the last instruction to target that architectural register (in which case register is marked ready).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Graduation copies the value from the reorder buffer into the architectural register file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The sole use of the architectural register file is to recover from exceptions and branch mispredictions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Exceptions and branch mispredictions, recognized at graduation, cause the architectural file to be copied to the future file, and all registers marked as ready in the rename file.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] There is usually no way to reconstruct the state of the future file for some instruction intermediate between decode and graduation, so there is usually no way to do early recovery from branch mispredictions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In both schemes, instructions are inserted in-order into the issue queues, but are removed out-of-order.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] If the queues do not collapse empty slots, then they will either have many unused entries, or require some sort of variable priority encoding for when multiple instructions are simultaneously ready to go.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Queues that collapse holes have simpler priority encoding, but require simple but large circuitry to advance instructions through the queue.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Reservation stations have better latency from rename to execute, because the rename stage finds the register values directly, rather than finding the physical register number, and then using that to find the value.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This latency shows up as a component of the branch misprediction latency.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Reservation stations also have better latency from instruction issue to execution, because each local register file is smaller than the large central file of the tag-indexed scheme.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Tag generation and exception processing are also simpler in the reservation station scheme, as discussed below.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The physical register files used by reservation stations usually collapse unused entries in parallel with the issue queue they serve, which makes these register files larger in aggregate, and consume more power, and more complicated than the simpler register files used in a tag-indexed scheme.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Worse yet, every entry in each reservation station can be written by every result bus, so that a reservation-station machine with, e.g., 8 issue queue entries per functional unit will typically have 9 times as many bypass networks as an equivalent tag-indexed machine.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Consequently, result forwarding consumes much more power and area than in a tag-indexed design.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Furthermore, the reservation station scheme has four places (Future File, Reservation Station, Reorder Buffer and Architectural File) where a result value can be stored, whereas the tag-indexed scheme has just one (the physical register file).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Because the results from the functional units, broadcast to all these storage locations, must reach a much larger number of locations in the machine than in the tag-indexed scheme, this function consumes more power, area, and time.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Still, in machines equipped with very accurate branch prediction schemes and if execute latencies are a major concern, reservation stations can work remarkably well.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The IBM System/360 Model 91 was an early machine that supported out-of-order execution of instructions; it used the Tomasulo algorithm, which uses register renaming.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The POWER1 from 1990 is the first microprocessor that used register renaming and out-of-order execution.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] This processor implemented register renaming only for floating-point loads.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The POWER1 had only one FPU, so using renaming for floating-point instructions other than memory operation was unnecessary.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The POWER2 had multiple FPUs, so renaming was used for all floating-point instructions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Later revisions of the design starting with the R12000 used a partially variable priority encoder to mitigate this problem.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Early out-of-order machines did not separate the renaming and ROB/PRF storage functions.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] For that matter, some of the earliest, such as Sohi's RUU or the Metaflow DCAF, combined scheduling, renaming, and storage all in the same structure.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Most modern machines do renaming by RAM indexing a map table with the logical register number.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] E.g., P6 did this; future files do this, and have data storage in the same structure.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] However, earlier machines used content-addressable memory (CAM) in the renamer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] E.g., the HPSM RAT, or Register Alias Table, essentially used a CAM on the logical register number in combination with different versions of the register.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] In many ways, the story of out-of-order microarchitecture has been how these CAMs have been progressively eliminated.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Small CAMs are useful; large CAMs are impractical.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The P6 microarchitecture was the first microarchitecture by Intel to implement both out-of-order execution and register renaming.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The P6 microarchitecture was used in Pentium Pro, Pentium II, Pentium III, Pentium M, Core, and Core 2 microprocessors.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] The Cyrix M1, released on October 2, 1995, was the first x86 processor to use register renaming and out-of-order execution.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/register-renaming] Other x86 processors (such as NexGen Nx686 and AMD K5) released in 1996 also featured register renaming and out-of-order execution of RISC μ-operations (rather than native x86 instructions).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] A **re-order buffer** (**ROB**) is a hardware unit used in an extension to Tomasulo's algorithm to support out-of-order and speculative instruction execution.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] The extension forces instructions to be committed in-order.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] The buffer is a circular buffer (to provide a FIFO instruction ordering queue) implemented as an array/vector (which allows recording of results against instructions as they complete out of order).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] There are three stages to the Tomasulo algorithm: "Issue", "Execute", "Write Result".
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] In an extension to the algorithm, there is an additional "Commit" stage.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] During the Commit stage, instruction results are stored in a register or memory.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] The "Write Result" stage is modified to place results in the re-order buffer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] Each instruction is tagged in the reservation station with its index in the ROB for this purpose.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] The contents of the buffer are used for data dependencies of other instructions scheduled in the buffer.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] The head of the buffer will be committed once its result is valid.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] Its dependencies will have already been calculated and committed since they must be ahead of the instruction in the buffer though not necessarily adjacent to it.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] Data dependencies between instructions would normally stall the pipeline while an instruction waits for its dependent values.
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] The ROB allows the pipeline to continue to process other instructions while ensuring results are committed in order to prevent data hazards such as Read after Write (RAW), Write after Read (WAR) and Write after Write (WAW).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] The consequences of the re-order buffer include precise exceptions and easy rollback control of target address mis-predictions (branch or jump).
[src:cpu-microarchitecture/reorder-buffer] When jump prediction is not correct or a nonrecoverable exception is encountered in the instruction stream, the ROB is cleared of all instructions (by setting the circular queue tail to the head) and reservation stations are re-initialized.
